WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.990 --> 00:00:08.460
- I was born here

00:00:08.460 --> 00:00:11.490
and people tease me that
I sometimes still refer

00:00:11.490 --> 00:00:13.350
to this as my house.

00:00:13.350 --> 00:00:14.350
- Steve Jobs is on the kitchen counter.

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:17.850
- I know.
- Steve Jobs is staring at you

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:19.470
every time you cook.

00:00:19.470 --> 00:00:20.490
- My mom knew Steve well

00:00:20.490 --> 00:00:22.170
because she wrote some of the first grants

00:00:22.170 --> 00:00:24.990
to bring the Mac into schools.

00:00:24.990 --> 00:00:27.570
And so my mom was one of the
first digital programs in a

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:29.460
journalism program at school.

00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:32.490
And so my mom used to like
show up at the house, knock,

00:00:32.490 --> 00:00:34.350
knock, knock and be like,
I need some more Macs.

00:00:38.190 --> 00:00:41.820
- Anne Wojcicki. Bay area
native, cycling enthusiast,

00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:45.090
co-creator of the
Breakthrough Prize in science

00:00:45.090 --> 00:00:49.173
and co-founder of the
personal genetics company 23andMe.

00:00:50.430 --> 00:00:52.050
23andMe inspired millions of people

00:00:52.050 --> 00:00:54.000
to spit in tubes in exchange

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:55.530
for a glimpse at their genetic code.

00:00:56.460 --> 00:01:00.120
- So you now have the first
FDA approved consumer

00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:01.140
genetic test.

00:01:01.140 --> 00:01:03.630
- What you might call
Anne Wojcicki, a pioneer.

00:01:03.630 --> 00:01:05.730
- We're going to
fundamentally change things.

00:01:05.730 --> 00:01:09.060
It was a biotech darling
at one point worth nearly

00:01:09.060 --> 00:01:10.680
$6 billion

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:14.460
before it all collapsed

00:01:14.460 --> 00:01:16.830
and Wojcicki was forced to resign in order

00:01:16.830 --> 00:01:18.600
to win it back from the outside.

00:01:19.800 --> 00:01:21.690
- From that moment, it
was like a little bit

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:26.100
of a total reckoning,
like, what am I going to do?

00:01:27.570 --> 00:01:32.400
What she did was buy the
company for $305 million in cash,

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:36.570
restructure it as a nonprofit,
and retake the title of CEO.

00:01:36.570 --> 00:01:38.850
Should we call it a
comeback or not just yet?

00:01:38.850 --> 00:01:41.940
- It's an evolution. Probably
more than the comeback.

00:01:41.940 --> 00:01:44.670
I joined her for a
fast-paced two day romp

00:01:44.670 --> 00:01:47.490
through the hills around
Stanford's campus, where she

00:01:47.490 --> 00:01:50.160
talked to me about winning her
job back, co-parenting

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:54.060
with Google co-founder Sergey
Brin, losing her sister Susan,

00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:56.280
former CEO of YouTube,

00:01:56.280 --> 00:01:58.800
and the day her own
board turned against her,

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:02.640
- Those people were friends of hers.

00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:04.170
And how could they have done that?

00:02:04.170 --> 00:02:05.490
- The shock will never wear off.

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:08.045
All while making me work for it.

00:02:09.585 --> 00:02:12.480
- Is this supposed to make my
blood pressure go up or down?

00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:14.520
- Down. It's going to go down.

00:02:14.520 --> 00:02:16.203
And my camera crew, too.

00:02:16.203 --> 00:02:18.736
Now that she's back at the helm,

00:02:18.736 --> 00:02:21.420
Wojcicki is looking
forward to better days.

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:23.536
- I definitely have a master's

00:02:23.536 --> 00:02:25.452
in hard things right now.

00:02:25.452 --> 00:02:27.427
So when I write the PhD

00:02:27.427 --> 00:02:29.627
thesis, I'll share it with you, okay?

00:02:38.010 --> 00:02:40.350
- Okay, so we're biking.
- We're biking, we're biking.

00:02:40.350 --> 00:02:41.370
- So what's your biking routine?

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:42.540
- Okay, so my biking routine,

00:02:42.540 --> 00:02:44.070
I bike every day because it's freedom.

00:02:44.070 --> 00:02:46.350
So I always bike in the
morning, I show up in the office

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:48.960
and I'm happy and I bike home

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:50.490
and then I can kind of process everything

00:02:50.490 --> 00:02:52.020
that happened in the office that day.

00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:54.000
So nobody ever, like when it's raining out

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.413
and I can't bike, people know it's a
different personality.

00:02:57.413 --> 00:02:58.996
- They don't want to talk to you.

00:02:58.996 --> 00:03:00.754
- I'm just going to be more cranky.

00:03:03.471 --> 00:03:06.695
As kids we rode all around and
we used to like hang out

00:03:06.695 --> 00:03:10.930
and play in all these flowers.
We played in all of this.

00:03:10.930 --> 00:03:13.060
Now we're going to Kite Hill.

00:03:13.060 --> 00:03:16.030
So you might be surprised
to learn that this is

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:18.100
where we used to fly kites.

00:03:18.100 --> 00:03:20.680
- Wojcicki grew up in
an illustrious family.

00:03:20.680 --> 00:03:22.060
Her father Stanley, chair

00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:25.000
of the physics department at
Stanford. Her sister Janet,

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.180
a doctor and professor.
Susan, who's credited

00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:31.396
with persuading Google to buy
YouTube, and the matriarch,

00:03:31.396 --> 00:03:36.362
Esther. Celebrated high school
teacher, friend of Steve Jobs

00:03:36.362 --> 00:03:39.880
and self-styled parenting expert. Wojcicki

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:43.030
studied biology at Yale, then
took a job on Wall Street

00:03:43.030 --> 00:03:44.590
before returning to California.

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:49.360
That's when she met her future
husband, Sergey Brin, one

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:51.490
of the Stanford PhD students working out

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:55.300
of her sister Susan's garage
on something called search.

00:03:55.300 --> 00:03:56.766
Specifically, Google.

00:03:56.766 --> 00:04:00.155
Brin gave 23andMe a loan,
later repaid when Google

00:04:00.155 --> 00:04:02.140
took a stake in the company.

00:04:03.430 --> 00:04:07.060
The couple divorced in 2015,
but remain on good terms.

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:11.050
- We can put our bikes down
and then we can look around.

00:04:11.050 --> 00:04:12.808
- How about that?
- Yes.

00:04:12.808 --> 00:04:13.933
You were on the front lines

00:04:13.933 --> 00:04:15.700
of Google obviously.

00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:18.460
Did that empower you

00:04:18.460 --> 00:04:20.470
or did that sort of give you

00:04:20.470 --> 00:04:22.270
like a motivation to push through?

00:04:22.270 --> 00:04:25.960
- Yeah, I think the thing
that I learned from them

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:28.480
and from like frankly
like this whole culture is

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:32.860
that it's okay to try
and it's okay to fail.

00:04:32.860 --> 00:04:35.380
Like the main thing is like
the continuous pursuit of

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:36.820
what you're interested in.

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:39.820
- You buy the company
back with your own money.

00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:42.671
- Yes, thank God. Yeah.
- Why come back?

00:04:42.671 --> 00:04:44.804
- Why come back?
- Oh, why come back?

00:04:44.804 --> 00:04:45.820
- Why not start something new?

00:04:45.820 --> 00:04:47.860
- I love it. I love what we do.

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:51.130
At the end of the day I was
like, okay, if I don't buy it,

00:04:51.130 --> 00:04:54.010
I'm probably in my head
always regretting it.

00:04:55.330 --> 00:04:57.940
- How'd it feel to write that
check? That's a big check.

00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:01.720
- I mean, in some ways it's
like a privilege that I can.

00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:05.230
23andme I think is so incredibly valuable

00:05:05.230 --> 00:05:07.720
and it's now a gift to society.

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:10.960
And so this should be the open science

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:13.690
platform for the world.

00:05:13.690 --> 00:05:17.290
Like to make discoveries about
like the foundations of life,

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:18.790
make discoveries about, you know,

00:05:18.790 --> 00:05:21.273
what is health, about diseases,

00:05:21.273 --> 00:05:23.380
Alzheimer's, like everything.

00:05:23.380 --> 00:05:27.010
- The business model seemed
reasonable. On one side,

00:05:27.010 --> 00:05:30.190
a consumer product that was
making waves in pop culture.

00:05:30.190 --> 00:05:33.820
See there's a new company
called 23andMe, and

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:37.570
because of them, 23 people
now say their father is me.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:42.400
On the other, a treasure trove of DNA data

00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:45.010
that could theoretically be
used to develop treatments

00:05:45.010 --> 00:05:46.720
to deadly diseases.

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:48.760
Any drugs or diseases in particular

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:50.020
that you are particularly we working on

00:05:50.020 --> 00:05:51.370
excited about? We're a whole rate

00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:53.680
- Oncology, immunology, neurology,

00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:55.330
cardiovascular, metabolic disease.

00:05:55.330 --> 00:05:58.580
So this is major breakthrough
stuff you're doing.

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:01.340
- The company went public
in 2021 via a richer

00:06:01.340 --> 00:06:02.930
Branson back deal.

00:06:02.930 --> 00:06:07.460
The stock boomed and Wojcicki
became a self-made billionaire.

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:10.250
She and Brin had also been
buying up commercial real estate

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:11.690
in nearby Los Altos,

00:06:11.690 --> 00:06:14.360
a passion project which
eventually took over.

00:06:15.515 --> 00:06:20.360
- It's a little bit like
real life monopoly like you,

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:21.500
you get and buy a building

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:24.110
and then you can find
amazing business leaders

00:06:24.110 --> 00:06:26.570
and you can support them.

00:06:26.570 --> 00:06:28.280
- Everything seemed to be coming up. Anne,

00:06:33.110 --> 00:06:36.800
- Oh
- You think she owned the place?

00:06:38.150 --> 00:06:41.720
But the newly public company
was about to run into trouble

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:45.380
after peaking at a market
cap of $5.7 billion,

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:47.750
the stock tanked 23

00:06:47.750 --> 00:06:50.750
and me wasn't selling enough
kits to keep Wall Street happy.

00:06:50.750 --> 00:06:54.680
Then hackers got a hold of
data from 6.9 million 23

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:58.760
and me profiles, which certainly
didn't help suddenly 23

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:00.020
and Me was out of cash.

00:07:01.100 --> 00:07:04.760
Looking back, if you see
a blind spot, what was it?

00:07:04.760 --> 00:07:06.770
- I think there's like a number
of things that we did wrong

00:07:06.770 --> 00:07:09.860
and I think first and foremost,
you know, there's aspects

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:11.450
that are like totally unsexy

00:07:11.450 --> 00:07:13.730
but are really important
like corporate structure.

00:07:13.730 --> 00:07:15.620
I'd go and meet with an investor

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:17.420
and they would say like,
what's your identity?

00:07:18.290 --> 00:07:21.920
Are you a consumer company?
Are you a diagnostic company?

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:23.840
Are you a therapeutics company?

00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:25.610
And we'd say like, oh, we're all of them.

00:07:25.610 --> 00:07:27.080
And like, that's amazing.

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:30.800
And at that stage we were
at, it was too complex.

00:07:32.150 --> 00:07:36.020
- On March 23rd, 2025, the
company filed for bankruptcy.

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:46.640
I headed to New York to meet up

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:48.710
with veteran journalist Kristin V. Brown,

00:07:48.710 --> 00:07:50.330
to find out more about what happened

00:07:50.330 --> 00:07:52.280
to the once promising biotech company.

00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:56.060
You've been covering Anne
Wojcicki for a long time.

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:59.600
What's your impression of
her as a person and as a CEO?

00:07:59.600 --> 00:08:02.870
- There's kind of a cult
of personality around her

00:08:02.870 --> 00:08:04.400
because she's so nice

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:07.610
and so enthusiastic about what she does.

00:08:07.610 --> 00:08:10.010
I mean, nobody believes in the power

00:08:10.010 --> 00:08:12.170
of the genome more than Anne Wojcicki.

00:08:12.170 --> 00:08:15.800
- What was the promise of DNA
when 23andMe first started

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:17.480
and what changed?

00:08:17.480 --> 00:08:21.130
- So what changed is not that 23andMe
had a bad idea.

00:08:21.130 --> 00:08:23.390
At the time, it was a great idea.

00:08:23.390 --> 00:08:25.910
- In 2003, scientists finished the first

00:08:25.910 --> 00:08:27.560
map of the human genome.

00:08:27.560 --> 00:08:29.840
Francis Collins, the
leader of the project,

00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:32.990
said we would have a DNA based
designer drug for Alzheimer's

00:08:32.990 --> 00:08:35.000
and cancer by 2020.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:36.350
- With this profound new knowledge.

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:37.520
Humankind is on the verge

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:40.580
of gaining immense new power to heal

00:08:40.580 --> 00:08:41.660
- In the eighties and nineties

00:08:41.660 --> 00:08:43.190
they were having all these breakthroughs

00:08:43.190 --> 00:08:47.660
where they were finding single
genes for diseases, right?

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:49.430
Like Huntington's disease.

00:08:49.430 --> 00:08:51.320
We thought that most
diseases would be like that.

00:08:51.320 --> 00:08:54.290
That there would be one gene for diabetes,

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:57.390
that there would be one gene
that made you more at risk for,

00:08:57.390 --> 00:08:58.740
you know, lung cancer.

00:08:58.740 --> 00:09:00.780
But it's not like that.
There are many, many,

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:02.940
many genes involved in diabetes.

00:09:02.940 --> 00:09:04.530
And the fact is

00:09:04.530 --> 00:09:06.900
that biology is not only still pretty

00:09:06.900 --> 00:09:09.720
mysterious to us, right?
We don't know a lot.

00:09:09.720 --> 00:09:11.470
- Hmm. What is 23andMe's

00:09:11.470 --> 00:09:14.190
biggest challenge in your opinion?

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:16.500
- I think 23andMe's biggest
challenge that most people

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:18.450
who want to take a DNA test kit have

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:20.910
already, have already done it.

00:09:20.910 --> 00:09:25.020
And you know, how do you grow if people

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:26.700
fundamentally don't want your product?

00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:32.730
- Welcome to my, my crazy home.

00:09:32.730 --> 00:09:35.520
- This is the house you grew up in.
- It is.

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.890
- I think every square inch
of wall has a picture on it.

00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:41.850
- It's very much a history of our lives.

00:09:42.990 --> 00:09:44.850
So that's little me,
but like more importantly,

00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:45.930
this is little me.

00:09:45.930 --> 00:09:49.890
- Okay.
- And so that's Susan, that's Janet

00:09:49.890 --> 00:09:51.900
and that's my grandmother Rose.

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:56.490
And that's me. You know,
Susan and Janet dominated

00:09:56.490 --> 00:09:59.340
and so I had that luxury a
little bit of like sitting back

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:02.160
and watching and just
like seeing what they did

00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:04.500
and like what mistakes they made.

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:06.720
And so like even at my first job,

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:09.480
like I remember thinking like
my first year is not about

00:10:09.480 --> 00:10:11.040
speaking, it's about observing.

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:13.530
Hmm. And I've always kind
of been that way is like,

00:10:13.530 --> 00:10:16.170
I want to understand the
situation before I jump in.

00:10:17.310 --> 00:10:19.530
- A year ago, almost exactly, the company

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:20.976
filed for bankruptcy.

00:10:20.976 --> 00:10:22.860
Tell me about that day and that

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:23.860
decision.

00:10:23.860 --> 00:10:25.560
- I mean it's, it's remarkable

00:10:25.560 --> 00:10:29.160
to think it was almost a
year ago. I had resigned so

00:10:29.160 --> 00:10:31.860
that I could be part of
the bidding process, knowing

00:10:31.860 --> 00:10:35.310
that there was a likely chapter 11 filing.

00:10:35.310 --> 00:10:37.080
You know, I think some of
the things that surprised me,

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:41.700
like I was, you know, suddenly out.

00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:45.090
I had no, none of my email
from 20 years or 19 years.

00:10:45.090 --> 00:10:48.840
My calendar, like everything,
like my life, it was just

00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:53.840
so personal and like
suddenly I didn't have it.

00:10:53.940 --> 00:10:55.800
You know, it's like a death.

00:10:55.800 --> 00:10:57.690
Like what do you do the
day after someone dies?

00:10:57.690 --> 00:10:59.460
Like you kind of look at everything,

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:02.250
like you look at the clouds
and you look at the sky and,

00:11:02.250 --> 00:11:05.742
and it's different and
everything is a different shade.

00:11:05.742 --> 00:11:07.433
- Around the same time her

00:11:07.433 --> 00:11:09.750
company was falling apart, Wojcicki

00:11:09.750 --> 00:11:12.900
and her family suffered three real deaths.

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:15.390
Her father passed away at age 86.

00:11:15.390 --> 00:11:19.860
Susan, who never smoked,
died at 56 of lung cancer.

00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:23.220
And Susan's 19-year-old son
Marco passed away from an

00:11:23.220 --> 00:11:24.480
accidental overdose.

00:11:26.100 --> 00:11:27.780
Susan was fighting cancer.

00:11:27.780 --> 00:11:29.670
While you were fighting for your company,

00:11:30.515 --> 00:11:31.920
did you talk to her about it?

00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:33.720
- Yeah, I mean like even when,

00:11:33.720 --> 00:11:36.480
when she was in her last
month of life, she was like,

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:40.260
well like send me your 10 Q
and I'll give you feedback.

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:43.380
She was a big supporter and
she was always trying to help.

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:45.060
She was like always the big sister.

00:11:46.830 --> 00:11:50.880
- In 2024, your board
resigned all at once.

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:52.560
The board put out a statement

00:11:52.560 --> 00:11:55.750
after of work, we have yet
to receive a fully financed,

00:11:55.750 --> 00:11:57.880
fully diligent, actionable proposal

00:11:57.880 --> 00:12:00.430
that is in the best
interests of shareholders.

00:12:00.430 --> 00:12:03.130
It is also clear that we differ
on the strategic direction

00:12:03.130 --> 00:12:04.960
for the company going forward.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:07.450
Because of that and your
concentrated voting power,

00:12:07.450 --> 00:12:08.650
we resign from the board.

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:12.040
Now some of these people
are people who've sung your

00:12:12.040 --> 00:12:13.090
praises for decades.

00:12:13.090 --> 00:12:17.170
Investors like Roelof Botha,
Patrick Chung, Neal Mohan,

00:12:17.170 --> 00:12:19.720
who took over as CEO when Susan left.

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:22.930
What conversations did you have with them

00:12:22.930 --> 00:12:24.640
and how did that feel?

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:28.540
- I mean, it was a really complicated time

00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:31.150
because we'd set up a special committee.

00:12:31.150 --> 00:12:32.170
I was still CEO,

00:12:32.170 --> 00:12:34.600
but it was almost like the
special committee took over to,

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:36.965
to take on major decisions.

00:12:38.140 --> 00:12:40.810
So it was a surprise for me
when they were saying, you know,

00:12:40.810 --> 00:12:43.240
like, oh, there's, we have a disagreement

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:44.980
where I was like, like what?

00:12:44.980 --> 00:12:48.310
Like, like what? What
were we disagreeing about?

00:12:48.310 --> 00:12:52.570
I was working incredibly
hard to put together a bid.

00:12:52.570 --> 00:12:55.270
It was hard because Susan died August 9th

00:12:55.270 --> 00:12:57.310
and the board resigned a few weeks later.

00:12:57.310 --> 00:12:59.380
- Have you talked to any of them since?

00:12:59.380 --> 00:13:00.610
- I've engaged with a couple.

00:13:01.810 --> 00:13:03.550
- So who's in your burn book

00:13:03.550 --> 00:13:05.980
and who's, who's, who stuck with you?

00:13:05.980 --> 00:13:08.800
- I think they will stay
anonymous in my, in my burn book.

00:13:08.800 --> 00:13:10.270
People have their own motivations.

00:13:10.270 --> 00:13:11.920
People have their own reasons why.

00:13:13.330 --> 00:13:15.700
And it was a really complicated situation.

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:18.820
And I should emphasize I was
one of the largest shareholders

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:21.160
and I was going to do whatever I could

00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:25.000
to be in the best interest of
the mission and shareholders.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:26.860
It was an unbelievable surprise to me.

00:13:28.090 --> 00:13:30.670
- Bloomberg reached out to the
board members who resigned,

00:13:30.670 --> 00:13:33.605
all but one declined to
comment or didn't respond.

00:13:33.605 --> 00:13:37.371
Patrick Chung, one of the
earliest investors in 23andMe

00:13:37.371 --> 00:13:41.054
said, "it became necessary
to reorganize 23andMe

00:13:41.054 --> 00:13:42.490
and cut some programs,"

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:44.950
but that the company's mission
"remains fully alive" under

00:13:44.950 --> 00:13:46.783
Wojcicki's leadership.

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:51.010
I want to talk about the data
breach that exposed the data

00:13:51.010 --> 00:13:53.950
of millions of users that
wasn't stored securely.

00:13:53.950 --> 00:13:57.310
When you look back on that,
what do you think went wrong?

00:13:57.310 --> 00:14:00.370
How did you, or how did
the team let that happen?

00:14:00.370 --> 00:14:02.020
- I've never called it a data breach

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:05.080
because it wasn't actually
a breach of our systems.

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:07.990
Usernames and passwords by other companies

00:14:07.990 --> 00:14:11.770
that had been breached were
released into the dark web.

00:14:11.770 --> 00:14:13.660
And what we found is there was 13

00:14:13.660 --> 00:14:18.220
or 14,000 of those that matched in

00:14:18.220 --> 00:14:23.220
23andMe. And you know,
we elected to notify,

00:14:23.500 --> 00:14:27.070
you know, obviously the
13, 14,000 individuals,

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:30.220
but also everyone that they
were genetically connected to

00:14:30.220 --> 00:14:34.930
and, and that's how the
numbers became so large. Data

00:14:34.930 --> 00:14:37.360
and security are top priorities

00:14:37.360 --> 00:14:39.160
and we always take that really seriously.

00:14:39.160 --> 00:14:43.840
We always have. And you learn
from, you learn every day.

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:45.280
And the most important thing is

00:14:45.280 --> 00:14:47.710
to be vigilant and stay on top of it.

00:14:47.710 --> 00:14:50.650
- The highly publicized sale,
stoked fears about privacy.

00:14:50.650 --> 00:14:54.950
Attorneys general told
consumers to delete their data

00:14:54.950 --> 00:14:58.100
and Congress called Wojcicki to testify.

00:14:58.100 --> 00:15:00.920
- Failing to safeguard Americans'
data from these hostile

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:04.490
actors would not only be a
critical violation of privacy,

00:15:04.490 --> 00:15:07.760
but also a national security catastrophe.

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:10.670
- Drugmaker Regeneron initially
won the auction for most

00:15:10.670 --> 00:15:12.380
of 23andMe's assets,

00:15:12.380 --> 00:15:16.760
but Wojcicki persuaded the bankruptcy
court to reopen the case.

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:19.550
Part of her argument was that
the data would remain with

00:15:19.550 --> 00:15:22.430
23andMe instead of being
sold to Big Pharma.

00:15:22.430 --> 00:15:24.230
And in the end she won.

00:15:25.730 --> 00:15:29.480
So ultimately your offer was
accepted $305 million.

00:15:29.480 --> 00:15:31.370
- It was. On round two.

00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:33.170
Let's not forget round two

00:15:33.170 --> 00:15:35.690
because that was, there
was real work, girl.

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:40.940
- Did you celebrate or was
it not that kind of a day?

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:43.310
- The day that I won is surreal.

00:15:43.310 --> 00:15:46.370
Regeneron put out tons of
press around how they won.

00:15:46.370 --> 00:15:48.590
They were out here meeting with my team,

00:15:48.590 --> 00:15:50.090
you know, they were in it to win it.

00:15:50.090 --> 00:15:54.320
And so reopening the auction was a battle.

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:58.340
And part of what Regeneron
negotiated for was the last look,

00:15:58.340 --> 00:16:01.790
meaning that they had the
ability to give the last bid.

00:16:01.790 --> 00:16:05.690
And I was devastated, like
totally flat out devastated

00:16:05.690 --> 00:16:07.430
because I didn't have, you know,

00:16:07.430 --> 00:16:10.130
Regeneron has 16 billion
on their balance sheet.

00:16:10.130 --> 00:16:11.450
Like I can't compete.

00:16:11.450 --> 00:16:16.040
And so I had to have peace with
like, I'm going to lose it.

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:18.110
And I was like, but at least I'm going to,

00:16:18.110 --> 00:16:19.460
I'm going to go down fighting.

00:16:20.810 --> 00:16:24.440
I'm not going to just,
you know, hand it over.

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:29.270
And so that morning I walked
in was like, you know,

00:16:29.270 --> 00:16:32.000
sat down, you know, it's like, you know,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:33.680
a giant table of lawyers.

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:35.660
It's like a really expensive table.

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:39.260
And you know, Regeneron
said they declined to bid

00:16:39.260 --> 00:16:41.450
and I couldn't stop screaming.

00:16:42.290 --> 00:16:45.110
I was like screaming, jumping
up and down. I was crying.

00:16:45.110 --> 00:16:47.210
I was like raw emotion.

00:16:47.210 --> 00:16:49.070
That's like all, it was like,
I was like out of control.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:50.600
It was like out of body experience.

00:16:50.600 --> 00:16:52.400
- What's the hardest thing
about being a founder

00:16:52.400 --> 00:16:54.290
after a very public stumble.

00:16:54.290 --> 00:16:55.700
- You know, it's hard
because you want to win

00:16:55.700 --> 00:16:57.500
and you want to be successful.

00:16:57.500 --> 00:16:58.700
And for me,

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:02.900
success was not just
about the monetary side,

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:06.200
but it was also the success of humanity

00:17:06.200 --> 00:17:08.485
and helping millions

00:17:08.485 --> 00:17:12.110
and millions of people
benefit from their genome.

00:17:12.110 --> 00:17:14.930
And you know, we're at 13 million today,

00:17:14.930 --> 00:17:16.970
which is the world's largest, you know,

00:17:16.970 --> 00:17:18.470
recontactable data set.

00:17:18.470 --> 00:17:20.090
But to do the things that we want to do,

00:17:20.090 --> 00:17:23.900
particularly in an AI world,
you want hundreds of millions

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:28.010
to really realize the dream
of understanding the code

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:32.330
of life and having
personalized prevention.

00:17:32.330 --> 00:17:33.590
You know, I look at the MAHA movement,

00:17:33.590 --> 00:17:35.240
I look at everyone here
like we're suffering

00:17:35.240 --> 00:17:36.980
with chronic disease, like we're suffering

00:17:36.980 --> 00:17:38.060
with all these different issues.

00:17:38.060 --> 00:17:40.460
Susan had lung cancer, like

00:17:40.460 --> 00:17:43.640
how can I understand our health?

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:46.640
And to understand it, you need data

00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:49.080
and you need data that's
collected in the right way

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:51.330
and you need engaging with people.

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:54.390
- Wojcicki took me to the food court

00:17:54.390 --> 00:17:55.920
she started, where we talked about her

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:57.090
philosophy around health.

00:17:57.960 --> 00:18:01.530
- All right, welcome
to State Street Market.

00:18:01.530 --> 00:18:03.450
- Love it. So you built this place.

00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:06.181
- We built this place. What do you

00:18:06.181 --> 00:18:07.530
want? You want to get a mango lassi?

00:18:07.530 --> 00:18:10.890
- Ooh yeah, that sounds good.
- Let's get mango lassis.

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:15.240
- You know, you've always
been really into preventative

00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:17.280
health and you've been really critical

00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:18.630
of the healthcare system.

00:18:19.530 --> 00:18:21.840
Do you think the system is broken?

00:18:21.840 --> 00:18:24.720
- There's so much money
off the dysfunction

00:18:24.720 --> 00:18:27.210
that you can never change from within.

00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:29.850
I think you have to start outside.

00:18:29.850 --> 00:18:34.440
And what makes me so happy
now is it everything

00:18:34.440 --> 00:18:36.780
23andMe did was so hard
in those early days.

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:39.420
Like there wasn't even online consent.

00:18:39.420 --> 00:18:42.090
The idea of having a patient come

00:18:42.090 --> 00:18:44.400
and get, you know,
information on their own was

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:45.660
like radical.

00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:49.710
So the fact that there's like,
there's us, there's Hims,

00:18:49.710 --> 00:18:52.950
there's Ro, there's Midi,
there's you know, Hello Heart.

00:18:52.950 --> 00:18:56.130
I mean there's like an entire industry

00:18:56.130 --> 00:18:58.800
that has made healthcare easier.

00:18:58.800 --> 00:19:00.510
- What's your take on the MAHA movement?

00:19:00.510 --> 00:19:02.250
Make America Healthy Again?
- Ooh.

00:19:02.250 --> 00:19:05.310
My mom was like very early, you know,

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:07.920
teaching us about BHT and preservatives

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:10.980
and you never want to eat,
you know, red food coloring

00:19:10.980 --> 00:19:12.810
and that it can create hyperactivity.

00:19:12.810 --> 00:19:14.070
So one thing I realized also

00:19:14.070 --> 00:19:17.790
with my mom is the first time
I asked for my medical record,

00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:20.640
it came with this note across
the top that said, as all

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:24.150
of us in pediatrics know
this mom can be quite

00:19:24.150 --> 00:19:25.980
uncontrollable at times.

00:19:25.980 --> 00:19:27.750
My mom had a tragedy when she was little,

00:19:27.750 --> 00:19:30.000
her little brother ate a bottle of aspirin

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.880
and they couldn't get
proper care and he died.

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:35.280
And so my mom always had
this mindset is like,

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:36.600
if you don't take care of yourself

00:19:36.600 --> 00:19:39.630
and if you don't advocate
for yourself, nobody will.

00:19:39.630 --> 00:19:41.100
And so like time

00:19:41.100 --> 00:19:44.130
after time my mom, you know,
we'd have the experience

00:19:44.130 --> 00:19:46.290
of like going to the doctor saying like,

00:19:46.290 --> 00:19:48.240
oh there's this issue
or there's this problem

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:50.280
and not feeling heard.

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:53.460
And then we switch. Like
even I had this issue, I went

00:19:53.460 --> 00:19:56.490
to the dentist and she
insisted on X-raying my mouth.

00:19:56.490 --> 00:19:57.990
I was like, I don't want a X-ray.

00:19:57.990 --> 00:20:00.480
So she kicked me out
of the chair and I left

00:20:00.480 --> 00:20:02.160
and I had to go find a new dentist.

00:20:02.160 --> 00:20:05.970
And the MAHA movement for
me is reflective of the fact

00:20:05.970 --> 00:20:09.720
that people are hurting
and they don't feel heard

00:20:10.650 --> 00:20:12.090
and they want to see change.

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:15.060
- I am a MAHA mom.

00:20:16.260 --> 00:20:17.940
- Is that a correct statement by the way?

00:20:20.100 --> 00:20:21.990
- About 41 percent of
Americans say they support

00:20:21.990 --> 00:20:24.540
the MAHA movement,
which covers a wide range

00:20:24.540 --> 00:20:26.730
of claims about food vaccines

00:20:26.730 --> 00:20:29.520
and cell phone radiation,
often with little evidence

00:20:29.520 --> 00:20:31.080
to support them.

00:20:31.080 --> 00:20:34.170
But skepticism of the medical
establishment is growing.

00:20:34.170 --> 00:20:36.060
And maybe that's an opening for

00:20:36.060 --> 00:20:38.880
23andMe to find its
momentum again, this time

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:42.960
as a nonprofit. How does the
whole nonprofit thing work?

00:20:42.960 --> 00:20:45.480
- 23andMe was always a
mission driven company.

00:20:45.480 --> 00:20:47.380
We were always focused on impact.

00:20:47.380 --> 00:20:49.960
How many people are
signing up to participate

00:20:49.960 --> 00:20:52.210
and how many lives are we saving?

00:20:52.210 --> 00:20:54.100
How many papers are we generating?

00:20:54.100 --> 00:20:57.220
Is it being translated into
something that's meaningful

00:20:57.220 --> 00:20:58.690
for society?

00:20:58.690 --> 00:21:00.790
We're going to be
measured on questions like

00:21:00.790 --> 00:21:03.340
that, no longer on like, did you

00:21:03.340 --> 00:21:05.350
generate a bottom line for us?

00:21:05.350 --> 00:21:09.190
And that's why we're growing
as a nonprofit is to say,

00:21:09.190 --> 00:21:11.980
we're coming back, and we're, the mission

00:21:11.980 --> 00:21:13.960
and the dream is still there.

00:21:13.960 --> 00:21:15.940
We're going to get to a
hundred million people.

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:18.040
We're absolutely going to
learn the code of life.

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:20.110
We're absolutely going to define

00:21:20.110 --> 00:21:22.480
what a personalized
prevention plan means for each

00:21:22.480 --> 00:21:24.070
and individual person.

00:21:24.070 --> 00:21:26.530
And we're going to eliminate
preventable deaths.

00:21:26.530 --> 00:21:29.440
And I can achieve that as a
nonprofit the same way I could

00:21:29.440 --> 00:21:30.610
achieve that as a for-profit.

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:35.110
- 23andMe'S model as a
nonprofit is to sell kits,

00:21:35.110 --> 00:21:36.460
take donations,

00:21:36.460 --> 00:21:39.790
and then use the data for
research both internally

00:21:39.790 --> 00:21:41.380
and with external partners.

00:21:42.850 --> 00:21:44.380
In the last year, it's contributed

00:21:44.380 --> 00:21:47.470
to published research on
obesity drugs, cannabis,

00:21:47.470 --> 00:21:50.800
and using AI to predict
conditions based on genes.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:54.460
Billionaire Ron Conway
has committed to donate

00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:55.510
to the new foundation.

00:21:56.710 --> 00:21:59.650
It's a sign of one of
Wojcicki's superpowers.

00:21:59.650 --> 00:22:02.740
She knows a lot of powerful
people with deep pockets

00:22:02.740 --> 00:22:04.420
and people like her.

00:22:05.860 --> 00:22:08.890
But there are downsides to
being entangled with the elite

00:22:10.210 --> 00:22:11.590
Wojcicki's name,

00:22:11.590 --> 00:22:14.320
along with Brin's, appears
in the investigation

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:15.730
of disgraced financier

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:16.730
Jeffrey Epstein,

00:22:17.800 --> 00:22:20.320
whose assistant once ordered so many

00:22:20.320 --> 00:22:23.140
23andMe test kits that the
company flagged his request

00:22:23.140 --> 00:22:24.400
and canceled the order

00:22:24.400 --> 00:22:27.250
when it was revealed they
were for use outside the US.

00:22:29.200 --> 00:22:33.070
- Jeffrey Epstein was apparently
obsessed with genetics

00:22:33.070 --> 00:22:36.098
and lacing the human race
with his DNA.

00:22:36.098 --> 00:22:38.350
Ghislaine Maxwell
emailed Epstein about you

00:22:38.350 --> 00:22:40.780
directly, saying "be very nice to her.

00:22:40.780 --> 00:22:44.140
Not stupid. She's
interested in mapping DNA.

00:22:44.140 --> 00:22:46.060
She is key smiley face."

00:22:47.020 --> 00:22:49.210
Did you ever encounter Jeffrey Epstein?

00:22:49.210 --> 00:22:51.520
Did he ever talk to you about DNA?

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:56.520
- We met him once and I don't
remember talking about DNA.

00:22:56.560 --> 00:22:58.930
- I mean so many powerful
people including tech leaders,

00:22:58.930 --> 00:23:01.180
almost all of them men,
got caught in his web.

00:23:01.180 --> 00:23:03.460
How does this happen?

00:23:03.460 --> 00:23:06.010
- I, I think that there
was a circle of like people

00:23:06.010 --> 00:23:09.730
who like, hey, you meet this
person, you meet that person.

00:23:09.730 --> 00:23:12.250
I'm going to this event,
I'm going to this conference

00:23:13.180 --> 00:23:16.690
and you, you end up interacting.

00:23:16.690 --> 00:23:20.680
- Was it on the island?
- So we knew, you know, we went

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:25.240
to the island once that was
reported and it was short,

00:23:26.410 --> 00:23:29.830
but you know, he was, Jeffrey
Epstein was in the TED network

00:23:29.830 --> 00:23:32.650
and other areas like he was
kind of in the circle,

00:23:32.650 --> 00:23:35.350
but it was, it was pretty limited for us.

00:23:38.050 --> 00:23:40.630
- Nobody likes to be asked
about Jeffrey Epstein,

00:23:40.630 --> 00:23:43.570
but Wojcicki says she's an open book.

00:23:43.570 --> 00:23:46.310
You're not scared to
talk about hard things

00:23:46.310 --> 00:23:49.190
or things that other people
don't want to talk about.

00:23:49.190 --> 00:23:50.630
Where does that come from?

00:23:50.630 --> 00:23:51.920
- I have nothing to hide.

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:54.530
I've had like very public failures.

00:23:54.530 --> 00:23:58.490
I've had very public divorce.
I've had really hard times.

00:23:58.490 --> 00:24:00.500
You know, I always think
about like the people

00:24:00.500 --> 00:24:03.920
who helped me along the way,
like what is it that I can do

00:24:03.920 --> 00:24:05.780
that also helps other people?

00:24:05.780 --> 00:24:08.030
And frankly when I talk
about it, it helps me.

00:24:08.030 --> 00:24:10.280
- What's your relationship
like with Sergey now?

00:24:10.280 --> 00:24:12.890
- Sergey's been a great co-parent for me.

00:24:12.890 --> 00:24:14.180
You can't go through like the kind

00:24:14.180 --> 00:24:16.370
of crazy life you have, we've had,

00:24:16.370 --> 00:24:19.610
and like not

00:24:19.610 --> 00:24:21.500
have a deep affection.

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:24.770
And I feel like, like we've
raised a couple really

00:24:24.770 --> 00:24:26.300
amazing children.

00:24:26.300 --> 00:24:30.650
- You had a third child on
your own with a sperm donor.

00:24:30.650 --> 00:24:33.470
What went into that decision for you?

00:24:33.470 --> 00:24:37.280
- Yeah, I, I mean I can't
help talking about it

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:40.910
and smiling a lot because
I feel every day like I'm

00:24:40.910 --> 00:24:42.410
so lucky.

00:24:43.640 --> 00:24:46.400
I really, I like, I didn't
think I could get pregnant

00:24:46.400 --> 00:24:47.400
- At 45!

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:48.710
- I know at 45, a hundred percent.

00:24:48.710 --> 00:24:50.840
I mean I think that's where I
look at like all these things,

00:24:50.840 --> 00:24:52.700
like when you go into something

00:24:52.700 --> 00:24:55.580
with low expectations, what happens?

00:24:55.580 --> 00:24:58.040
But I went in saying
like, I'm not, I'm never,

00:24:58.040 --> 00:24:59.090
it's never going to happen.

00:24:59.090 --> 00:25:01.520
So like why am I even
like, I was like, I'm,

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:03.290
I'm doing it just to make sure

00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:05.300
that I don't feel guilty
that I didn't try.

00:25:05.300 --> 00:25:09.140
because if you don't try, you
can't. You have no chance.

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:10.880
- What's something people assume about

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:12.740
you but always get wrong.

00:25:12.740 --> 00:25:15.530
- I tend to not worry about
what people are assuming,

00:25:15.530 --> 00:25:17.180
but I know people definitely come to me

00:25:17.180 --> 00:25:19.640
and they're like, oh you're very grounded.

00:25:19.640 --> 00:25:22.640
I'm like, well why
would I not be grounded?

00:25:23.960 --> 00:25:26.210
I was like, I live with my
sister, I have my children.

00:25:26.210 --> 00:25:29.240
There's plenty of people
to try to keep me grounded.

00:25:31.250 --> 00:25:32.840
- Another beautiful day.
- You're seeing

00:25:34.520 --> 00:25:36.980
Wojcicki background headquarters.

00:25:36.980 --> 00:25:39.860
- I ended my day with
Wojcicki, her sister Janet,

00:25:39.860 --> 00:25:42.830
and her mother Esther in the
backyard of their family home

00:25:42.830 --> 00:25:45.830
to reflect on the challenges
of the last two years

00:25:45.830 --> 00:25:48.200
and finally settle the question of how

00:25:48.200 --> 00:25:50.210
to pronounce their Polish surname.

00:25:50.210 --> 00:25:52.790
I do want to start with a
lesson on pronunciation

00:25:52.790 --> 00:25:54.830
because nobody gets it right.

00:25:54.830 --> 00:25:56.855
- Ms. Anne Whoa-gee-key.

00:25:56.855 --> 00:26:00.688
- Ms. Whoa-jo-ski.
Did I say it wrong?

00:26:00.688 --> 00:26:02.779
- Uh, Ms. Whoa-jiskey.
It's Whoa-jiskey, right?

00:26:02.779 --> 00:26:03.830
- And I thought I had it right

00:26:03.830 --> 00:26:05.000
but then when you said it, I was like,

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:08.210
I don't say it quite
like that. So I say Wah-jit-ski.

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:09.440
- Yeah, that's fine.
- That's good.

00:26:09.440 --> 00:26:10.610
- But you said woo.

00:26:10.610 --> 00:26:13.701
- No, whoa. It's like whoa.
Like whoa, whoa.

00:26:13.701 --> 00:26:16.610
- Like Whoa-just-ski.
- Jiss.

00:26:16.610 --> 00:26:18.350
- It's like Whoa-jet-skiing.

00:26:18.350 --> 00:26:21.050
- No it's not.
- Well I'm just trying to make it -

00:26:21.050 --> 00:26:23.555
- There's no consensus in
this family. Let's just like -

00:26:23.555 --> 00:26:24.555
- Okay.

00:26:24.555 --> 00:26:25.388
Okay. And you're obviously used

00:26:25.388 --> 00:26:27.320
to people saying it wrong
and spelling it wrong.

00:26:27.320 --> 00:26:28.790
- Oh yeah. The minute they say anything

00:26:28.790 --> 00:26:30.833
that sounds reasonable, I say yes.

00:26:32.360 --> 00:26:35.960
- I'm curious what you both
think seeing Anne having gone

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:37.070
through this era of survival.

00:26:37.070 --> 00:26:38.420
We talked about survival.

00:26:38.420 --> 00:26:41.300
- I mean it's remarkable.
It's really, it's remarkable.

00:26:41.300 --> 00:26:43.500
Like everything that
Anne has gone through,

00:26:43.500 --> 00:26:45.270
- You know, I had a feeling

00:26:45.270 --> 00:26:47.880
that she was going to be
just strong and resilient.

00:26:48.900 --> 00:26:51.840
But I can tell you as
a mom I couldn't watch

00:26:52.800 --> 00:26:54.420
because it was hard for me.

00:26:54.420 --> 00:26:57.540
It is very reassuring for me
to see her on the other side.

00:26:57.540 --> 00:26:59.130
And she has a great company.

00:27:00.060 --> 00:27:01.170
- You know, when I got divorced

00:27:01.170 --> 00:27:03.210
and it was hard, I remember I
had this therapist was like,

00:27:03.210 --> 00:27:07.800
you have to do one thing a
day that makes you happy.

00:27:07.800 --> 00:27:09.000
Mm. Like that's just for you.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:10.860
And I've kind of lived by that.

00:27:10.860 --> 00:27:12.480
We couldn't control Susan getting sick.

00:27:12.480 --> 00:27:13.980
We couldn't control Marco dying.

00:27:13.980 --> 00:27:17.820
Like I couldn't control
aspects of 23andMe.

00:27:17.820 --> 00:27:21.540
And so the thing I can
control is like making myself

00:27:21.540 --> 00:27:22.950
happy and optimistic.

00:27:22.950 --> 00:27:26.550
- I interviewed Susan many
times and she was always so kind

00:27:26.550 --> 00:27:30.600
and so generous with, with her
advice about how to be a mom

00:27:30.600 --> 00:27:32.580
and how to have a big job

00:27:32.580 --> 00:27:36.840
and that, yeah, you, you
could do that at the same time

00:27:36.840 --> 00:27:39.030
and you could actually
be good at both things.

00:27:39.030 --> 00:27:43.080
There are so few women in high profile,

00:27:43.080 --> 00:27:45.510
powerful positions in tech.

00:27:45.510 --> 00:27:49.350
Do you see that as another
part of this tragedy?

00:27:49.350 --> 00:27:52.230
- Yes, a hundred percent.
- For sure.

00:27:52.230 --> 00:27:54.210
I think every day,

00:27:54.210 --> 00:27:57.000
like I wish I could get
Susan's perspective on the

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:59.100
world, you know?

00:27:59.100 --> 00:28:00.780
And there's not tons

00:28:00.780 --> 00:28:04.500
of female leaders in the tech space.

00:28:04.500 --> 00:28:06.570
- We always thought she might
be the next CEO of Google.

00:28:07.500 --> 00:28:10.200
- I know, I know. Look, Susan was amazing.

00:28:10.200 --> 00:28:13.620
And what was fun for
us, like we'd be skiing

00:28:14.550 --> 00:28:17.130
and you know, we all
like bring our different,

00:28:17.130 --> 00:28:19.050
like you have all the kids
and there's this chaos

00:28:19.050 --> 00:28:20.250
and Janet has her world like,

00:28:20.250 --> 00:28:22.380
and Susan would be
like, I got to like deal

00:28:22.380 --> 00:28:26.520
with these crazy things that
are happening on YouTube and,

00:28:26.520 --> 00:28:27.780
and then she'd be there and she'd be like,

00:28:27.780 --> 00:28:29.970
oh can you bring the diaper bag?

00:28:29.970 --> 00:28:33.720
You know? I went to the
Oscars every year with Susan

00:28:33.720 --> 00:28:37.020
and Susan was so funny because
she like didn't really care.

00:28:37.020 --> 00:28:38.520
She was like, I'm just going to buy

00:28:38.520 --> 00:28:41.490
like a dress at Macy's, like on sale.

00:28:41.490 --> 00:28:44.340
But she kind of had that
perspective as like,

00:28:44.340 --> 00:28:45.720
it's not like, it's not
that important for us.

00:28:45.720 --> 00:28:47.730
Like no one's like watching us.

00:28:47.730 --> 00:28:51.690
- Anne Wojcicki tried to recruit
Susan to 23andMe to no avail.

00:28:51.690 --> 00:28:53.820
But she's had more success with Janet.

00:28:53.820 --> 00:28:56.505
You now work with Anne.

00:28:56.505 --> 00:28:58.950
- Yes. Yes.
- And I think you also live together.

00:28:58.950 --> 00:29:01.410
- Yes. You know, it wasn't an ask,

00:29:01.410 --> 00:29:02.912
it was like, you're
going to be on the board.

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:06.780
- Does she also let you
borrow her pants in exchange?

00:29:08.820 --> 00:29:10.445
I mean, how does this work? Really?

00:29:12.780 --> 00:29:15.180
- I had to quickly check
the outfit to see whether

00:29:15.180 --> 00:29:16.980
that was mine or truly hers.

00:29:18.630 --> 00:29:21.030
- Well that's one way to
stay aligned with your board.

00:29:23.010 --> 00:29:25.650
It's too early to say whether
a nonprofit structure will

00:29:25.650 --> 00:29:28.080
help Wojcicki achieve her ambitions.

00:29:28.080 --> 00:29:30.960
23and Me still needs to
persuade a lot more people

00:29:30.960 --> 00:29:32.310
to buy its tests.

00:29:32.310 --> 00:29:35.880
But Wojcicki as one early
investor put it, has a willful

00:29:35.880 --> 00:29:39.060
ignorance of constraints.
In Silicon Valley,

00:29:39.060 --> 00:29:40.920
that's usually considered a good thing.

00:29:42.070 --> 00:29:44.320
What are the chances she pulls this off?

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:48.430
- As a science reporter, I had
learned a long time ago to,

00:29:48.430 --> 00:29:49.660
you know, never say never.

00:29:49.660 --> 00:29:52.480
Right? Like we're learning
things all the time

00:29:52.480 --> 00:29:56.680
and our conception of human
biology is constantly changing.

00:29:58.330 --> 00:30:01.342
- So you haven't given up on
the dream it sounds like.

00:30:01.342 --> 00:30:02.980
- Yeah. Enable each person

00:30:02.980 --> 00:30:05.830
to have their own
personalized prevention path

00:30:05.830 --> 00:30:08.950
and accelerate discoveries
broadly like in every

00:30:08.950 --> 00:30:11.080
area. And we're going to do that.

00:30:11.080 --> 00:30:13.270
- The dream is alive guys.
- It's alive.

00:30:13.270 --> 00:30:14.560
- It's alive. Does anyone have a kite?

00:31:00.375 --> 00:31:04.480
- She's my mother. Who's uncontrollable?

00:31:04.480 --> 00:31:05.860
- The matriarch. Wait, wait, wait.

00:31:05.860 --> 00:31:08.740
Esther, can you tell us about
knocking on Steve Jobs door

00:31:08.740 --> 00:31:10.330
and asking for computers?

00:31:10.330 --> 00:31:13.210
- Oh, I did knock. He
came over to my class.

00:31:13.210 --> 00:31:14.680
I said I need some computers.

00:31:14.680 --> 00:31:16.810
He's like, if you don't tell anybody

00:31:16.810 --> 00:31:19.510
where you got them, I'll give you some.

00:31:19.510 --> 00:31:21.045
- Well, you're telling people now. Okay.

